{"id":"2112.06021","submitter":"Raghavendra Kulkarni","authors":"Raghavendra G. Kulkarni","title":"Solution of single parameter Bring quintic equation","comments":"10 pages, 3 tables","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, we propose a new method to obtain a solution to a\nsingle-parameter Bring quintic equation of the form, $x^{5}+x=a$, where $a$ is\nreal. The method transforms the given quintic equation to an infinite but\nconvergent series expression in $(x/a)$, which is further transformed to a\nquartic equation in a novel fashion. The coefficients of the quartic equation\nso obtained are some kind of infinite series expressions in $a^{-4}$, which are\ntermed as \\textit{ultraradicals}. The quartic equation is then solved and its\none real solution is picked; further using this, the real solution of quintic\nequation, $x^{5}+x=a,$ is extracted. The ultraradicals used in this method\nconverge for $|a| > 1$; hence the method can be used when $|a| > 1$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 11 Dec 2021 16:38:59 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 29 Dec 2021 06:25:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-30"}
