{"id":"2112.06139","submitter":"Xiao Yan Xu","authors":"Xu Zhang, Gaopei Pan, Xiao Yan Xu, Zi Yang Meng","title":"Fermion sign bounds theory in quantum Monte Carlo simulation","comments":"11 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.106.035121","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el cond-mat.stat-mech hep-lat hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Sign problem in fermion quantum Monte Carlo (QMC) simulation appears to be an\nextremely hard problem. Traditional lore passing around for years tells people\nthat when there is a sign problem, the average sign in QMC simulation\napproaches zero exponentially fast with the space-time volume of the\nconfigurational space. We, however, analytically show this is not always the\ncase and manage to find physical bounds for the average sign. Our understanding\nis based on a direct connection between the sign bounds and a well-defined\npartition function of reference system and could distinguish when the bounds\nhave the usual exponential scaling, and when they are bestowed on an algebraic\nscaling at low temperature limit. We analytically explain such algebraic sign\nproblems found in flat band moir\\'e lattice models at low temperature limit. At\nfinite temperature, a domain size argument based on sign bounds also explains\nthe connection between sign behavior and finite temperature phase transition.\nSign bounds, as a well-defined observable, may have ability to ease or even\nmake use of the sign problem.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 12 Dec 2021 03:29:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 26 Jun 2022 03:58:46 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-07-20"}
